"https://bensblinds.com/blog\"},{\"@type\":\"ListItem\",\"position\":3,\"name\":\"Window Treatments for Chicago Rental Apartments (Renter-Friendly Options)\",\"item\":\"https://bensblinds.com/blog/window-treatments-chicago-rental-apartments\"}]}</script><nav aria-label=\"breadcrumb\" style=\"background:var(--surface-2);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);padding:0.625rem 1.5rem\"><div class=\"container\"><ol style=\"display:flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;list-style:none;margin:0;padding:0;font-size:0.8125rem;color:var(--text-3);font-family:var(--font-body);flex-wrap:wrap\"><li><a style=\"color:var(--text-3);text-decoration:none\" href=\"/\">Home</a></li><li style=\"opacity:0.5\">/</li><li><a style=\"color:var(--text-3);text-decoration:none\" href=\"/blog\">Blog</a></li><li style=\"opacity:0.5\">/</li><li style=\"color:var(--text-2);font-weight:500\">Window Treatments for Chicago Rental Apartments (Renter-Friendly Options)</li></ol></div></nav><div style=\"height:320px;overflow:hidden;background:var(--surface-2)\"><img src=\"/images/products/roller-hero.jpg\" alt=\"Renter-friendly roller shades in a Chicago apartment without permanent installation\" style=\"width:100%;height:320px;object-fit:cover;display:block\" loading=\"eager\" fetchPriority=\"high\" decoding=\"async\"/></div><article style=\"padding:3rem 1.5rem 4rem\"><div class=\"container\" style=\"max-width:760px\"><p style=\"font-size:0.8125rem;color:var(--text-3);font-family:var(--font-body);margin-bottom:0.75rem\">April 1, 2026<!-- -->· Ben&#x27;s Blinds Chicago</p><h1 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:800;font-size:clamp(1.5rem, 3.5vw, 2.25rem);color:var(--text);margin-bottom:1.25rem;line-height:1.2\">Window Treatments for Chicago Rental Apartments (Renter-Friendly Options)</h1><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);font-size:1.125rem;color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:2.5rem;border-left:3px solid var(--brand);padding-left:1rem\">Renting in Chicago doesn&#x27;t mean living with ugly aluminum blinds. These renter-friendly window treatment options add style and function without permanent installation — and you can take them with you when you move.</p><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Chicago renters face a specific challenge: most leases prohibit permanent modifications to windows, but landlord-provided aluminum blinds are often ugly, damaged, or inadequate for light control and privacy. The good news: there&#x27;s a growing category of renter-friendly window treatments that provide real style and function without requiring permanent installation — and since they&#x27;re yours, you take them to your next Chicago apartment when you move.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Understanding Your Lease: What&#x27;s Usually Allowed</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Most Chicago apartment leases fall into one of three categories regarding window treatments: &#x27;no permanent modifications&#x27; (most common), &#x27;no drilling into window frames&#x27; (slightly more permissive), or &#x27;no alterations whatsoever&#x27; (most restrictive, usually in luxury buildings with existing treatments). Before purchasing any window treatments, read your lease carefully. Key questions: Does it prohibit drilling into walls vs. window frames specifically? Does it require original blinds to remain in place? Does it address window treatment appearance from the exterior? When in doubt, ask your landlord in writing — many landlords are comfortable with non-permanent installations even when leases are vague.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Tension-Mount Solutions: No Hardware Required</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Tension-mount window treatments use spring-loaded tension to hold the shade or rod in place inside the window frame — no drilling, no screws, no damage. They work best in windows with consistent, parallel sides (most Chicago apartment double-hung windows qualify).</p><ul style=\"margin:0.75rem 0 0;padding:0;list-style:none;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.625rem\"><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Tension-mount roller shades: Available in blackout and light-filtering fabrics, fit windows up to approximately 48&quot; wide</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Tension-mount curtain rods: Allow standard curtain panels without drilling into walls or frames</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Cordless cellular shades with tension mount: Available from select manufacturers for windows up to 36&quot; wide</span></li></ul></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Command Strip and Adhesive Mount Options</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">3M Command strips and similar adhesive products have improved dramatically and now support window treatment hardware in many configurations. Adhesive-mount curtain rod brackets can support lightweight curtain panels (up to approximately 10 lbs per bracket). Adhesive-mount roller shade brackets are available from several manufacturers for lightweight roller shades. Important caveat for Chicago renters: test adhesive strength on your specific wall surface (plaster walls in Chicago vintage buildings can be more variable than drywall) and follow weight limits carefully. Remove adhesive hooks according to instructions when moving to minimize wall damage.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Outside-Mount with Minimal Holes</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">If your lease allows drilling (even reluctantly) and you&#x27;re planning to live in the apartment for a year or more, outside-mount window treatments installed with two small screws per bracket offer significantly better light control and aesthetics than tension-mount options. Small screw holes (1/8&quot; diameter) filled with matching spackling and touch-up paint on move-out are generally considered normal wear and tear and should not affect your security deposit. This is the most pragmatic option for Chicago renters staying 12+ months who want real light control and style.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">What to Avoid in Chicago Rentals</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Avoid permanent modifications that can&#x27;t be reversed: don&#x27;t install inside-mount brackets by drilling into window frames (these holes are difficult to fill and often visible), don&#x27;t remove or store landlord-provided blinds without explicit permission (you may be charged for their replacement even if you reinstall them), and don&#x27;t install heavy drapery hardware that requires wall anchors in plaster walls without testing first. Chicago&#x27;s older buildings often have lime plaster walls that are more fragile than modern drywall.</p><ul style=\"margin:0.75rem 0 0;padding:0;list-style:none;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.625rem\"><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Don&#x27;t drill into window frames — holes are difficult to repair</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Don&#x27;t remove landlord blinds without written permission</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Don&#x27;t use heavy wall anchors in vintage plaster without testing</span></li><li style=\"display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:0.625rem;font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:1rem;line-height:1.6\"><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" style=\"flex-shrink:0;color:var(--brand);margin-top:4px\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><polyline points=\"20 6 9 17 4 12\"></polyline></svg><span>Don&#x27;t use suction-cup mounting for anything other than sheer/lightweight panels</span></li></ul></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Curtain Panels: The Renter&#x27;s Best Friend</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">For Chicago renters who want maximum style flexibility, curtain panels on a tension-mount or adhesive-mount rod offer the widest aesthetic range with the least permanent commitment. Floor-to-ceiling curtain panels in a Logan Square vintage apartment, a Wicker Park loft, or a Lincoln Park garden unit can transform the look of a room dramatically. Pair blackout curtain panels with the existing landlord blinds for bedroom light control — the curtains cover the ugly blinds, add insulation, and provide blackout when drawn, all without any permanent modification.</p></div><div style=\"margin-bottom:1.75rem\"><h2 style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.375rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.75rem;margin-top:0.25rem\">Our Renter Services</h2><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);line-height:1.75;font-size:1.0625rem\">Ben&#x27;s Blinds works with Chicago renters as well as homeowners. We offer free in-home consultations for renters to assess your specific windows, lease restrictions, and goals. We stock tension-mount and adhesive-mount compatible products and can advise on what your lease actually allows vs. what it says. For renters in buildings where landlords are willing to negotiate, we&#x27;ve facilitated arrangements where landlords allow and sometimes contribute to window treatment upgrades that improve unit value — worth asking about if you&#x27;re on good terms with your building management.</p></div><div style=\"margin-top:3rem;padding:2rem;background:var(--surface-2);border-radius:var(--radius);border-left:4px solid var(--brand)\"><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:1.0625rem;color:var(--text);margin-bottom:0.5rem\">Ready for a free in-home consultation?</p><p style=\"font-family:var(--font-body);color:var(--text-2);font-size:0.9375rem;line-height:1.6;margin-bottom:1rem\">We come to you, measure every window, and give you a written quote on the spot. Serving all Chicago neighborhoods.</p><div style=\"display:flex;gap:0.75rem;flex-wrap:wrap\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary\" style=\"font-size:0.9375rem\" href=\"/quote\">Book Free Consultation</a><a href=\"tel:+13123610908\" class=\"btn btn-secondary\" style=\"font-size:0.9375rem\">(312) 361-0908</a></div></div></div></article><section style=\"padding:3rem 1.5rem 4rem;background:var(--surface-2);border-top:1px solid var(--border)\"><div cl